# 🎯 Why We Need Forward + Backward?

If we only used normal Kadane:

* We cannot efficiently compute "what happens if we remove one element in middle".

Using two arrays allows us to:

* Quickly get best left sum
* Quickly get best right sum
* Combine in O(1)

Overall complexity stays linear.

---

# ⏱ Time & Space Complexity

### Time Complexity:

* Forward pass → O(n)
* Backward pass → O(n)
* Deletion loop → O(n)

✅ **Total = O(n)**

---

### Space Complexity:

We use two extra arrays.

✅ **O(n) space**

---

# 🚀 Interview Explanation (Short Oral Version)

> "This is a modified Kadane problem.
> I compute forward maximum subarray sum ending at each index and backward maximum starting at each index.
> Then for each index, I simulate deleting that element by combining forward[i-1] and backward[i+1].
> Finally, I return the maximum of normal Kadane and all deletion cases.
> Time complexity O(n), space O(n)."

